<p>Store champagne bottles <strong>horizontally</strong> at a constant 50-55°F (10-13°C) with 70% humidity. Unlike still wines, champagne's crown cap and metal cage make it more sensitive to temperature fluctuations. Avoid light exposure and vibration, which can disturb the delicate secondary fermentation sediment and affect flavor development.</p>

<h3>Aging vs Spoilage Indicators</h3>
<p>Properly aged champagne displays <strong>deeper golden color</strong> and complex tertiary aromas of toast, nuts, and dried fruits. The mousse remains persistent but softer. Warning signs include excessive browning, flat bubbles, or oxidized sherry-like aromas indicating cork failure or improper storage. A slight decrease in effervescence is normal and often indicates a mature, well-developed champagne ready for enjoyment.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between champagne and other sparkling wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">True champagne can only be produced in the Champagne region of France using the traditional méthode champenoise, primarily from Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, and Pinot Meunier grapes. Other sparkling wines like Cava, Prosecco, or American sparkling wine may use different production methods and grape varieties. The chalk soils of Champagne and strict production regulations create champagne's distinctive mineral complexity and fine, persistent bubbles that set it apart from other sparkling wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose the best champagne for my budget?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For entry-level quality, look for Champagne houses like Nicolas Feuillatte or Taittinger Brut La Française ($40-60), which offer excellent house styles without prestige cuvée pricing. Mid-range options include Pol Roger White Foil or Billecart-Salmon Brut Reserve ($60-90) for exceptional craftsmanship. For special occasions, consider grower champagnes from producers like Egly-Ouriet or Pierre Peters, which often provide better value than famous grandes marques at similar price points.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose vintage or non-vintage champagne?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Non-vintage (NV) champagne represents the house style and offers consistent quality year after year, making it ideal for regular enjoyment and celebrations. Vintage champagne is only produced in exceptional years and showcases the unique character of that harvest, typically with more complexity and aging potential. For most occasions, premium NV champagnes from respected houses provide better value, while vintage champagnes are worth the premium for milestone celebrations or serious wine collecting.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the proper serving temperature for champagne?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve champagne at 43-46°F (6-8°C) to preserve the delicate bubbles and enhance the wine's aromatics. Chill the bottle in an ice bucket for 20-30 minutes or refrigerate for 3-4 hours before serving. Avoid over-chilling below 40°F, as this mutes the complex flavors and aromas that distinguish quality champagne from simple sparkling wine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I store an opened bottle of champagne?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">An opened bottle of champagne will maintain its effervescence for 3-5 days when properly stored in the refrigerator with a champagne stopper or sparkling wine closure. The wine's acidity and bubbles naturally preserve it longer than still wines. For best results, minimize air exposure and keep the bottle upright and cold—never use regular wine stoppers as they don't create the proper seal for pressurized wine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes when buying champagne?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming price equals quality—many overpriced prestige cuvées offer less value than excellent grower champagnes or smaller house selections. Avoid buying champagne that's been stored upright in warm conditions, as this degrades the wine and can cause premature aging. Don't overlook the importance of dosage levels; Extra Brut or Brut Nature styles showcase the wine's true character better than sweeter Demi-Sec for most palates.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good alternatives to champagne that taste similar?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Crémant de Loire and Crémant d'Alsace from France use the same traditional method as champagne and often provide exceptional quality at lower prices. English sparkling wines from producers like Nyetimber or Ridgeview are made from the same grape varieties and increasingly rival champagne in quality. For different but excellent sparkling wine experiences, consider high-quality Cava from Spain or premium Franciacorta from Italy, though these offer distinct flavor profiles rather than direct champagne substitutes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is expensive champagne really worth the premium price?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium champagnes justify their cost through superior vineyard sites, longer aging on lees, lower yields, and more selective harvesting and blending practices. However, diminishing returns often begin around $150-200, where marketing and prestige factor heavily into pricing. The sweet spot for quality-to-price ratio typically falls between $60-120 for exceptional champagnes that showcase true craftsmanship without luxury brand premiums.</p>
